## The Five Hundred Arhats' Request

The narrative then describes a crucial moment:

> "At that time, the twelve hundred arhats whose minds possessed independent mastery contemplated: 'We are delighted to have obtained what was never obtained before. If the World-Honored One were to grant each of us prophecy, just as he granted to the other great disciples, would this not be excellent?' The Buddha, knowing the thoughts of these beings, told Mahākāśyapa: 'These twelve hundred arhats—I shall now grant them, in sequential order in my presence, prophecies of supreme enlightenment.

> 'Among this assembly, my great disciple the monk Ājñātakauṇḍinya shall make offerings to sixty-two billion Buddhas, and then become a Buddha, bearing the name Universal-Illumination Tathāgata, Worthy One, Perfectly Enlightened One, Possessor of Luminous Conduct, Well-Gone One, Knower of the World, Unsurpassed One, Tamer of Beings, Teacher of Gods and Humans, Buddha, World-Honored One.¹⁰

> 'The five hundred arhats—Uruvelā-Kāśyapa, Gaya-Kāśyapa, Nādi-Kāśyapa, Kalodāyin, Udāyin, Aniruddha, Revata, Kapiṇa, Bakula, Cunda, Svāgata, and the others—shall all attain supreme enlightenment, bearing the same Buddha-name: Universal-Illumination.'"¹¹

This is a stunning egalitarian moment. Rather than singling out individual disciples with unique prophecies, the Buddha grants all five hundred the same Buddha-name and essentially the same fate. This affirms the universal applicability of the prophecy to all beings who have received the dharma.

The Buddha-name "Universal-Illumination" (普明) is the same given to Subodbi earlier (Chapter 6), suggesting that across different individuals and different teachers, the ultimate achievement is fundamentally identical—different paths, same destination.

¹⁰ **First Disciple [Ājñātakauṇḍinya]**: This disciple was traditionally known as the first to understand the Buddha's teaching after enlightenment. His inclusion here honors his historical role while universalizing the promise of Buddhahood.

¹¹ **Egalitarian Prophecy [Democratic Enlightenment]**: By granting all five hundred disciples the same prophecy with the same Buddha-name, the text affirms that enlightenment is not hierarchically distributed but universally available to all who practice.

