## Application to Buddhist Teaching

The arhats continue their understanding of the parable's application:

> "'The Buddha is the same. When he was a Bodhisattva, he taught us, causing us to generate the mind of supreme enlightenment. We subsequently forgot, not knowing, not understanding. Having attained the arhat path, we assumed we had attained ultimate extinction and great peace. We sustained ourselves with difficulty, considering our small attainments sufficient. Our aspiration for supreme enlightenment remained, undiminished.

> 'Now the World-Honored One awakens us, saying: "Monks, what you have attained is not ultimate extinction. I have long caused you all to plant the roots of merit for Buddhism. Through skillful means, I showed you the appearance of nirvana, and you took it as actual extinction. But this was not the case."¹⁶

> 'World-Honored One, now we know truly that we are Bodhisattvas, having received prophecies of supreme enlightenment. For this reason, we are exceedingly joyful and delighted, having obtained what was never obtained before.'"¹⁷

This application extends the parable's significance: the Buddha (like the friend) has been continuously teaching beings toward enlightenment, but out of ignorance, beings mistake provisional accomplishments for final goals. The "pearl" is Buddha-nature—always present, always available, yet requiring the Buddha's revelation for recognition.

The phrase "I have long caused you all to plant the roots of merit for Buddhism" suggests that the Buddha has been patiently cultivating beings' spiritual capacities across countless rebirths, waiting for the moment when they would be ready to recognize their true nature.

¹⁶ **Provisional vs. Ultimate [The Two Truths]**: The distinction between the "appearance of nirvana" (涅槃相) and actual nirvana parallels the Phantom City teaching—what appears as a destination is actually a waystation.

¹⁷ **Joyful Recognition [Transformation Through Knowledge]**: The arhats' joy at learning they are Bodhisattvas destined for Buddhahood surpasses their earlier satisfaction with arhat-status. The revelation of greater possibility transforms lesser achievements into mere steps.

