## Connections to Previous and Subsequent Teachings

**To Chapter 7 (Phantom City)**: The Pearl in the Garment parable complements the Phantom City parable. Where the Phantom City reveals that provisional goals (nirvana) are skillful means to ultimate goals (Buddhahood), the Pearl in the Garment reveals that beings already possess Buddha-nature—they need only recognize it. Together, the parables show that enlightenment is simultaneously (1) a journey requiring many stages and (2) the recognition of what was always present.

**To Chapter 5 (Medicinal Herbs)**: The principle of the Medicinal Herbs—that one dharma-rain nourishes all beings according to their nature—manifests in Chapter 8 as all five hundred disciples receiving the same prophecy (one name: Universal-Illumination) while remaining individually distinct. The unity and diversity are complementary expressions of the same truth.

**To Chapters 9-10**: The pattern established here of extending prophecies to broader groups will continue, eventually including women (Chapter 12) in the promise of Buddhahood, and finally extending to all beings who hear even a single verse of the Lotus Sutra (Chapter 10).

